{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"ff911a20-b18f-471f-8c12-b78973a79395","content":"The best approach is **`dotnet-trace`** with the `cpu-sampling` profile. Here's the workflow:\n\n**1. Install the tool inside the pod:**\n```bash\nkubectl exec -it <pod> -- bash\ndotnet tool install -g dotnet-trace\nexport PATH=\"$PATH:~/.dotnet/tools\"\n```\n\n**2. Find your app's PID:**\n```bash\ndotnet-trace ps\n```\n\n**3. Collect the trace** (e.g., 30 seconds):\n```bash\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling --duration 00:00:30\n```\n\n**4. Copy the `.nettrace` file out:**\n```bash\nkubectl cp <pod>:/path/to/trace.nettrace ./trace.nettrace\n```\n\n**5. Analyze** in Visual Studio, PerfView, or [Speedscope](https://www.speedscope.app) (use `--format speedscope` during collection for the latter).\n\n**Tips:**\n- If you can't install tools (distroless image), use a **sidecar** or the `DOTNET_DiagnosticPorts` env var with `dotnet-dsrouter` from outside the pod.\n- For production, consider `--buffersize 256` to reduce overhead.\n- `dotnet-counters monitor -p <PID>` is a quick first look before committing to a full trace.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"12c89871-aeb4-4fc8-b393-137e67de783c","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking for guidance on collecting a CPU trace from a .NET 8 app running in a Kubernetes pod on Linux. This is a knowledge/advice question, not a code task. I'll provide concise, practical guidance.","outputTokens":407,"requestId":"D7C6:100995:EED83F:11166CA:69F2B029"},"id":"9a55b9be-357d-4a9a-98af-e7f9f534e9aa","timestamp":"2026-04-30T01:28:19.351Z","parentId":"d06ceb2d-5754-4e2d-bf7c-be350fa06954"}
